<p>Théophile Peyron to Vincent van Gogh. Saint-Rémy-de-Provence, Tuesday, 1 July 1890.</p></vg:letContents>
<note type="sourceStatus" xml:id="sourceStatus">
<p>Original manuscript </p></note>
<note type="location" xml:id="location">
<p>Amsterdam, Van Gogh Museum, inv. no. b1064 V/1962</p></note>
<note type="date" xml:id="date">
<p>Letter headed: ‘1 juillet 1890’.</p></note>
<note type="additionalDetail" xml:id="additionalDetail">
<p>Hulsker assumed that this letter to Théophile Peyron, medical director of the asylum in Saint-Rémy, was addressed to Theo van Gogh (see Hulsker 1993-2, pp. 176-179). We think, however, that it was intended for Vincent. It is the answer to the letter in which Vincent proposes to give the orderlies 10 francs (<ref target="let891.xml">see letter 891</ref>). Moreover, the remarks about the addressee’s good health <ref target="#l-13">(ll. 13-20)</ref> and the success Peyron hoped he would have at exhibitions <ref target="#l-21">(ll. 21-25)</ref> must be addressed to Vincent.</p></note></vg:letDesc></sourceDesc></fileDesc></teiHeader>
